---
import ToolLayout from '@/components/tools/ToolLayout.astro';
import ToolCta from '@/components/tools/ToolCta.astro';
import SlugGenerator from '@/components/tools/SlugGenerator';
import { tools } from '@/data/tools';

const tool = tools.find((t) => t.slug === 'slug-generator')!;
---
<ToolLayout tool={tool}>
  <SlugGenerator client:load />

  <div slot="body" class="prose-page">
    <h2>What makes a good URL slug</h2>
    <p>
      A slug is the human-readable tail of a URL — the <code>webflow-cms-structure</code> in{' '}
      <code>/blog/webflow-cms-structure</code>. Good slugs are short, lowercase, hyphen-separated,
      and built from your target keyword with the filler words stripped. This generator lowercases,
      removes accents and punctuation, collapses spaces to hyphens, and trims the ends — exactly what
      a clean slug needs.
    </p>

    <h2>Slug rules worth knowing</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hyphens, not underscores.</strong> Google treats hyphens as word separators; underscores join words.</li>
      <li><strong>Lowercase only.</strong> Some servers treat <code>/About</code> and <code>/about</code> as different URLs.</li>
      <li><strong>Keep it lean.</strong> Drop stop words (a, the, of, to) unless they change the meaning.</li>
      <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t stuff dates or IDs</strong> unless the content is genuinely time-bound.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Changing a slug? Redirect it first</h2>
    <p>
      In Webflow, the CMS auto-generates a slug from the item name, but you can override it per item.
      If you rename a published slug, add a 301 from the old path before you publish or you&rsquo;ll
      lose the rankings and break inbound links. My{' '}
      <a href="/blog/webflow-sitemap-robots-canonical/">Webflow sitemap, robots & canonical guide</a>{' '}
      covers redirect handling, and the{' '}
      <a href="/blog/webflow-cms-structure/">CMS structure guide</a> covers naming collections and
      slugs so you don&rsquo;t have to rename them later.
    </p>

    <ToolCta />
  </div>
</ToolLayout>
